Yes, you can access the `appMyDirective` from `someOtherDirective` on the same element by simply injecting `appMyDirective` into `someOtherDirective`&#39;s constructor and call its property.

```ts
export class SomeOtherDirective implements OnInit {

  constructor(private myDir: MyDirective) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    this.myDir.disabled = true;
  }
}
```

[StackBlitz Example](https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-zmy2qc?embed=1&amp;file=src/app/two.directive.ts)

Using `@ContentChild` can work in certain circumstances to give direct access to another directive. This worked in my circumstance.

```
import { AfterContentInit, Directive } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;

@Directive({
  selector: &#39;[appMyDirective]&#39;,
})
export class AppMyDirective implements AfterContentInit {

  // query for the other directive
  @ContentChild(SomeOtherDirective, { static: false }) someOtherDirective!: SomeOtherDirective;

  constructor() { }

  // @ContentChild isn&#39;t available until this lifecycle hook
  ngAfterContentInit() {

    // interact with the other directive directly
    someOtherDirective.disabled = true;
  }
}

```

```
&lt;div appMyDirective someOtherDirective [disabled]=&quot;false&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
```

